1.10.8.2 The contextlib module
..............................

The new *note contextlib: 24. module provides some functions and a
decorator that are useful for writing objects for use with the ’*note
with: 29d.’ statement.

The decorator is called ‘contextmanager()’, and lets you write a single
generator function instead of defining a new class.  The generator
should yield exactly one value.  The code up to the *note yield: 480.
will be executed as the *note __enter__(): 907. method, and the value
yielded will be the method’s return value that will get bound to the
variable in the ’*note with: 29d.’ statement’s *note as: 8aa. clause, if
any.  The code after the *note yield: 480. will be executed in the *note
__exit__(): 908. method.  Any exception raised in the block will be
raised by the *note yield: 480. statement.

Our database example from the previous section could be written using
this decorator as:

     from contextlib import contextmanager

     @contextmanager
     def db_transaction (connection):
         cursor = connection.cursor()
         try:
             yield cursor
         except:
             connection.rollback()
             raise
         else:
             connection.commit()

     db = DatabaseConnection()
     with db_transaction(db) as cursor:
         ...

The *note contextlib: 24. module also has a ‘nested(mgr1, mgr2, ...)’
function that combines a number of context managers so you don’t need to
write nested ’*note with: 29d.’ statements.  In this example, the single
’*note with: 29d.’ statement both starts a database transaction and
acquires a thread lock:

     lock = threading.Lock()
     with nested (db_transaction(db), lock) as (cursor, locked):
         ...

Finally, the ‘closing(object)’ function returns `object' so that it can
be bound to a variable, and calls ‘object.close’ at the end of the
block.

     import urllib, sys
     from contextlib import closing

     with closing(urllib.urlopen('http://www.yahoo.com')) as f:
         for line in f:
             sys.stdout.write(line)

